Pages = {{369-378}},
Month = {{AUG}},
Abstract = {{This paper presents an introductory overview of the main issues that the
   digitalisation of industrial enterprises known as Industry 4.0 raises
   for social sciences. First, it will show that this technological
   transition-which, however, is unfinished and is seen to be in continuity
   with the so-called ``third industrial revolution{''}-cannot be
   interpreted with reference to a deterministic approach. It can be
   analysed more usefully as a range of decisions affecting the industrial
   policies of national states, the conception and design of machines,
   their adoption in production processes and finally their use by
   operators. Second, certain aspects of Industry 4.0 of special concern in
   terms of organisation of work processes will be analysed on various
   scales (from inter-company transactions to the specific tasks of
   individual workers). Finally, we will explain various hypotheses that
   social and economic research is developing with regard to the new
   technologies' controversial effects on employment.}},
