   (ISMI), Hsinchu, TAIWAN, AUG 07-09, 2016}},
Abstract = {{In this paper, we discuss scheduling problems for parallel batch
   processing machines, incompatible job families, and an arbitrary regular
   sum objective. Only jobs of the same family can be batched together. If
   the batches are assigned to machines and sequenced then the remaining
   subproblem of batch formation can be formulated as a transportation
   problem. A matheuristic framework is proposed that exploits this
   insight. Therefore, a biased random-key genetic algorithm is used to
   assign the batches to machines and sequence them on the single machines.
   In a first step, a feasible solution is determined for each chromosome
   based on list scheduling. If this solution is of sufficient quality, the
   corresponding instance of the transportation problem is solved to
   improve the current solution associated with the chromosome. The
   proposed framework is applied to a single batch machine scheduling
   problem with the weighted and unweighted number of tardy job objective.
   Scheduling jobs on parallel batch processing machines with the total
   weighted tardiness objective is used as a second application of the
   proposed framework. Computational experiments on benchmark instances
   from the literature demonstrate that the proposed framework is
   competitive or even outperforms state-of-the-art heuristics from the
   literature. In addition, we show by designed experiments that an
   iterative swap procedure used in previous research provides high-quality
   solutions, but it is outperformed by the transportation problem
   reformulation with respect to computing time. (C) 2017 Elsevier B.V. All
   rights reserved.}},
