Year = {{2017}},
Volume = {{16}},
Number = {{4}},
Pages = {{72-86}},
Abstract = {{The paper is devoted to the research of the nature of precarity. The
   authors explore the dual substance of precarity as both global and local
   phenomena. There are four major premises in the formation of precarity
   at the global and local levels: the divisions of labor markets deepening
   inequalities and asymmetries; the Fourth Industrial Revolution providing
   a demand for labor with machines replacing the living workforce; the
   changing nature of labor which dissolves the boundaries between
   alienated labor and independent private life; and the intervention of
   neoliberal ideology in practice, manifesting itself as invasion of the
   state and capital into the social production of individuals. The sum of
   these premises lead to the expansion of precarity in different forms,
   although mainly in the form of precarious employment. As a result,
   precarity is considered in the paper as a form of a new global order
   produced by the multitude of local disorders.}},
