Abstract = {{This paper presents position-based optimization methods to schedule the
   production of automatic cells of a wheel manufacturing factory.
   Real-time schedule is challenging when a cell is interrupted by various
   order changes. Given a sequence of orders to be scheduled, it is sorted
   based on an earliest due day policy, a mixed integer linear programming
   model is formulated, and then rolling-horizon optimization methods are
   used to timely find the near-optimal schedule by minimizing earliness
   and tardiness penalties with setup times of a manufacturing cell. In
   addition, an original schedule can be partial rescheduled with the
   preset order sequence by using the linear programming model.
   Experimental results show that the proposed method enables a wheel
   manufacturing cell to reschedule its three to five daily orders within
   the cycle time of a rim when there exist order changes, e.g., rush
   orders and customized orders. Hence, these proposed methods are
   promising to promptly derive the near-optimal schedule for satisfying
   the objective of mass customization for industry 4.0.}},
